Hi Candace, 

We know you're no stranger to the power of Git, and we want to make sure you're getting the most out of your Heroku experience. That's why we're reminding you about one of the most efficient tools in your developer toolkit: Git Push. 

Git Push allows you to deploy apps to Heroku directly from a Git repository. 

Why Git Push is Your Deployment Superpower:

Seamless Deployment : Send code changes from your local environment directly to your Heroku app. It's the simplest way to see your updates live! Version Control : Track your code history so it‚Äôs easier to roll back to previous versions if needed. Collaboration : Work smoothly with your team by sharing code and managing changes. 


Your Quick Git Push Refresher:

Initialize a Git Repository : If you haven't already, use git init in your project's directory. Commit Your Changes : Use git add and git commit to track your code modifications. Add Heroku Remote : Link your local repository to your Heroku app using heroku git:remote -a <your-app-name>. Push Your Code : Run git push heroku main (or master) to deploy your changes. 


For a more detailed walkthrough, check out our guide to deploying with Git: [https://hello.heroku.com/e/36622/articles-git/m6b4xj/1301115479/h/S2-tyrYwstCXLmoiJZPmGTh98-2uS7rolyFhLDNTRtI] . 

Pro Tip : Heroku is trusted by everyone from students to Fortune 500 companies for its ease of use and powerful features. Explore our documentation on other Git commands: [https://hello.heroku.com/e/36622/articles-github-integration/m6b4xm/1301115479/h/S2-tyrYwstCXLmoiJZPmGTh98-2uS7rolyFhLDNTRtI] to unlock even more powerful workflows. 

Happy coding! 

The Heroku Team

column7: The Good Student vs The Good Entrepreneur
column9:
Hey friends,

A few days ago, we kicked off the $1K Challenge that I‚Äôve been
mentioning here and on socials for the past few weeks. We‚Äôve got
1,300 people from 100+ countries taking part, all working towards
making their first $1,000 online. But more importantly, they‚Äôre
here to learn the key skills of independent income generation
that‚Äôll hopefully serve them for the rest of their lives.

It‚Äôs been really cool watching everyone‚Äôs introductions roll in.
We‚Äôve got doctors, software engineers, project managers, data
scientists, business analysts - basically a whole bunch of very
smart, very educated professionals who were probably pretty good
at school.

And this week, I‚Äôd like to share an idea I‚Äôve been noodling on
for a while - a pattern I keep seeing show up not just with our
challenge participants, but with anyone trying to build something
of their own: the good student vs the good entrepreneur mindset.

If you‚Äôre reading this email, you probably were (or are) a ‚Äúgood
student‚Äù - like me, you probably did well in school, you ticked
the right boxes, and your parents are/were probably proud that
you have a respectable career‚Ä¶ But, to succeed as an
entrepreneur, you kinda need to unlearn some of what school
taught you. The traits and skills that made you a good student
can often hold you back from being a good entrepreneur.

When you feel fear, what do you do? As a student, if you feel
fear, it‚Äôs because you just haven‚Äôt prepared enough. You need
more preparation. When I was stressed about an exam, my mum would
say, ‚ÄúIf you just studied harder, you‚Äôd feel better about it.‚Äù
And she was right - more preparation always helped in school.

But as an entrepreneur, when you feel fear, you want to think:
‚ÄúGreat, I‚Äôm stepping outside my comfort zone, and I‚Äôm going to
take action.‚Äù More preparation is actually the opposite of what
you want to be doing. Fear in entrepreneurship usually means
you‚Äôre about to do something that matters.

How do you approach problems? In school, the whole idea is that
you want to find the one right answer. There‚Äôs usually a correct
solution to the maths problem or the essay question, and your job
is to find it.

In entrepreneurship, you want to test multiple solutions. This is
a completely different way of operating.

I‚Äôve had conversations with so many people who say, ‚ÄúI just don‚Äôt
know what business idea to start.‚Äù They‚Äôre hung up on this
because they think there‚Äôs a right answer. They‚Äôre following the
school method - if I just do enough research and preparation and
introspection, I‚Äôll find the right answer, and then I‚Äôll never
waste time.

But real life doesn‚Äôt work like that. Almost no one who is
currently financially free got there from their very first idea.
There aren‚Äôt right answers in entrepreneurship - you just have to
keep testing things out.

What‚Äôs your relationship with mistakes? School teaches you to
avoid mistakes because there‚Äôs usually only one chance to submit
the thing. If you have to retake an exam, it‚Äôs considered a big
deal. ‚ÄúWhat are you, some kind of idiot?‚Äù - at least that was the
vibe at schools like mine.

But in entrepreneurship, you want to learn quickly from your
failures. You want to fail fast. No one in school tells you to
fail fast, but in entrepreneurship, failing fast and iterating
quickly is absolutely the way to go.

How much do you care what others think? In school, we care deeply
about peer approval. You really, really care what other people
think of you - your teachers, your classmates, your parents when
they see your report card.

As a good entrepreneur, you have to stop caring what other people
think. Your colleagues, your cousins, that old boss you had -
their opinions don‚Äôt pay your bills. The only opinion that truly
matters is your customer‚Äôs. I‚Äôm pretty sure that despite my best
efforts to highlight this during the challenge, this hurdle will
hold at least some of our students back. For some of them
(hopefully not a lot), the fear of what their friends or family
will think will stop them from putting their offer out there, and
immediately end any hope they have of pursuing independent
financial freedom.

When do you take action? School teaches you to learn everything
first. You don‚Äôt put something into practice until you‚Äôve done
all the theory. Complete the textbook, understand all the
concepts, then maybe do some practice problems.

In entrepreneurship, you want to learn just enough to take the
next step. This applies whether you‚Äôre building a business,
starting a creative project, or just trying something new.

Don‚Äôt wait until you‚Äôve learned everything before you start. You
don‚Äôt need to know your entire business plan before you test your
first idea. You don‚Äôt need to master every aspect of photography
before you take your first paid gig. You don‚Äôt need to be an
expert writer before you publish your first piece.

Learn just enough to take the next step. Then take it.

In my experience, it seems that about 80% of the obstacles people
face when building something of their own are emotional, and
about 20% are technical. The thing that will probably hold most
people back isn‚Äôt a lack of technical knowledge - it‚Äôs emotional
obstacles disguised as technical problems.

Your brain will tell you, ‚ÄúI just don‚Äôt know what the right
approach is yet. I need to do more research.‚Äù But actually, it‚Äôs
an emotional problem: ‚ÄúI‚Äôm afraid I‚Äôm not good enough‚Äù or ‚ÄúI‚Äôm
afraid people will judge me.‚Äù

The good news is that if you can recognise these patterns in
yourself, you‚Äôre already ahead of the game.

Whether you‚Äôre building a business, starting a side project, or
just trying something new in your life, these mindset shifts can
make an enormous difference. Most people never even try because
they‚Äôre waiting for the perfect moment, the perfect plan, or the
perfect level of preparation.

But that moment never comes. The only way to get good at
something is to start doing it badly first. And our students in
the $1k challenge are already starting to discover this 5 days
into the challenge, which is awesome to see.

Have a great week!

Ali xx

***********************
Hey there, Ghostwriter!
***********************

Welcome to the Premium Ghostwriting Blueprint‚Äîwhere every week we
help you knock down high-ticket clients as a Premium Ghostwriter
(even if you‚Äôre a full-time Freelance Writer, or you have a 9-5).

As a reminder: If you'd like to accelerate your trajectory as a
Premium Ghostwriter, don't forget to subscribe to my YouTube
channel (
https://click.convertkit-mail.com/v8u2pwwv82bmu9dmedcghvlpo8llh9/6qhehou700o820u9/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cueW91dHViZS5jb20vQG5pY29sYXNjb2xlNzc=
). Every week, I share new videos breaking down the skills,
frameworks, & strategies you need to build a profitable writing
business with 26,000+ others.

Today we want to help you start building trust as a ghostwriter
(and leverage it into more business than you know what to do
with).
-----------------------------------------------------------------

But before we get into it, here‚Äôs the 1 thing you need to know:

Being a highly-paid ghostwriter doesn‚Äôt require as much
credibility as you think.

In fact, your job, as a ghostwriter (and Solopreneur of any kind)
is to give people the language you want them to use when
introducing you. Because guess what? The more specific you are
about the language you want people to use, the easier it will be
for them to copy/paste that language and repeat it over and over
again.

When this happens, the game is won.

And your client will assume your are the right person for the
job‚Ä¶ BECAUSE THEY ARE USING YOUR LANGUAGE.

So, let‚Äôs walk through exactly how to do that for yourself.

**************************************
4 Ways To Build Trust As A Ghostwriter
**************************************

There are 4 ways to build trust as a ghostwriter‚Äîand to be
honest, none of them have anything to do with ‚Äúachieving‚Äù
something noteworthy.

#1: Your Bio

‚Äã
Here‚Äôs what happens when you get introduced to someone, or they
stumble across your profile online.

* They look you up.
* They click on your social profile.
* And the very first thing they do is read your bio.

And if your bio says, ‚ÄúI ghostwrite Educational Email Courses for
health and wellness brands ,‚Äù guess what they assume about you?
THAT YOU GHOSTWRITE EDUCATIONAL EMAIL COURSES FOR HEALTH AND
WELLNESS BRANDS!!!!!!

All you have to do is say what you do, right there, right away in
your bio, and people will internalize that as ‚Äúthe truth.‚Äù

Easy!

#2: Your Content
----------------

‚Äã
The second way you build trust as a ghostwriter is with the
content you publish.

When someone looks you up, or stumbles across one of your social
profiles, what‚Äôs the second thing they do after reading your bio?

* They scroll for a few seconds.
* They see what kind of content you are posting.
* And they decide if what you write about is for them or not.

In those few seconds, if they see you posting content like: ‚ÄúStar
Wars is the best movie of all time. Change my mind,‚Äù they are
probably not going to see you as ‚Äúan expert‚Äù in health and
wellness!

But if your bio says, ‚ÄúI ghostwrite Educational Email Courses for
health and wellness brands,‚Äù and then they scroll and almost all
your content is about how to ghostwrite Educational Email
Courses, the benefits of Educational Email Courses, the mistakes
people make when creating Educational Email Courses, etc., guess
what? THEY ARE GOING TO THINK YOU ARE AN ALL-STAR AT EDUCATIONAL
EMAIL COURSES!!!!!

#3: Your Own Asset
------------------

‚Äã
What‚Äôs the next thing someone does after reading your bio and
scrolling through your content?

* They click on your website.
* They scan through any resources.
* And they look for proof that backs up your bio, your content,
etc.

So, if you say you ghostwrite Educational Email Courses, wouldn‚Äôt
it make sense for you to have an Educational Email Course for
yourself? IT SURE WOULD!!!! And when they see you have your own
Educational Email Course pinned to the top of your profile, what
are they going to think? THAT YOU SURE DO KNOW A LOT ABOUT
EDUCATIONAL EMAIL COURSES!!!!!

#4: How You Pitch Your Service
------------------------------

Quick recap.

* Someone has read your bio.
* They‚Äôve scrolled through some of your content.
* Maybe they even typed in their email address and signed up for
a newsletter.

By the time they reach out to you, or you reach out to them,
they‚Äôre under the assumption that you are the go-to expert when
it comes to Educational Email Courses for this specific industry
(Health and Wellness brands, for example).

And if you get on the phone with them, and you can clearly
articulate the benefits of Educational Email Courses, the
mistakes founders and business owners make when writing
Educational Email Courses, and the outcomes they can unlock, then
guess what? YOU‚ÄôVE GOT YOURSELF A CLIENT‚ÄîBECAUSE YOU SURE DO SEEM
TO KNOW A LOT ABOUT EDUCATIONAL EMAIL COURSES!!!!!

Now, does this have anything to do with being an Internet
celebrity? Nope.

Does it have to do with you having a huge audience? Nope.

Does it have to do with you having a giant email list? Nope.

Literally the ONLY thing a prospective client wants to know is
whether or not you ‚Äúknow your stuff.‚Äù And the way they evaluate
whether or not you ‚Äúknow your stuff‚Äù comes down to these 4
credibility checks:

* Does your bio say so?
* Does your content show so?
* Does your own asset prove so?
* Does your conversation guarantee so?

If you pass the above 4 checks, you are going to have more
business than you know what to do with.

That‚Äôs it!

Dickie & Cole

Co-Founders, Premium Ghostwriting Academy

----------
# _**How It Works?**_

A **Print-on-Demand (POD)** business is an eCommerce model where products like t-shirts, mugs, posters, and more are customized and printed only after an order is placed. This eliminates the need for inventory and upfront production costs. 

‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî

**How It Works?**

1. **Choose a Niche**  
Select a specific audience or theme (e.g., dog lovers, gamers, fitness enthusiasts). Identify trends or popular topics to guide your designs.

2. **Create or Source Designs**  
Design eye-catching graphics or hire a designer. Ensure the designs align with your niche and are high quality.

3. **Select a Print-on-Demand Platform** 
Choose a platform that integrates with your store. Popular platforms include:

  1. **Printful:** Offers a wide range of products and integrations with Shopify.  

2. **Printify:** Features multiple suppliers and competitive pricing.  

3. **TeeSpring:** Provides a simple setup and social selling features.  

4. **Redbubble:** Includes a built-in marketplace for passive selling.

4. **Set Up Your Online Store**  
Use platforms like Shopify, Etsy, or WooCommerce to host your store. Integrate the POD service with your store for seamless order processing.

5. **Add Products**  
Upload your designs to the POD platform and create product listings. Add high-quality mockups and detailed descriptions to attract customers. 

6. **Market Your Products** 
Use social media, email marketing, and paid ads to reach your target audience. Leverage content marketing and influencers to build trust and drive traffic.

7. **Fulfill Orders**  
When a customer places an order, the POD platform automatically prints and ships the product directly to them.

8. **Earn Profits** 
You earn the difference between the price you set and the cost charged by the POD service. 

‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî

**Benefits of Print-on-Demand**

* **Low Startup Cost:** You don‚Äôt need to buy inventory upfront.  

* **Minimal Risk:** You only pay for products when you sell them.  

* **Customizable:** You can easily create and sell unique designs.  

* **Scalable:** The business can grow with minimal effort as orders increase.  

* **Automated Fulfillment:** POD platforms handle production and shipping for you.

‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî

**Challenges in Print-on-Demand**

1. **Lower Profit Margins**  
The cost per item is higher because each product is made individually.

2. **Dependence on Suppliers**  
Product quality and shipping times are determined by the POD platform you use.

3. **Limited Customization Options**  
Your product range is limited to what the POD supplier offers.

4. **Shipping Times**  
Production and delivery times can be longer compared to pre-stocked inventory.

----------
1. **Taplio** 

  1. Description: An all-in-one AI-powered tool for content inspiration, creation, scheduling, engagement, and lead generation on LinkedIn. 

2. Category: Social media growth 

3. Do they provide a free trial: Yes 

4. Website: [Link](https://taplio.com/?via=shushant) 

5. Core features: Search viral posts for ideas, write, edit, and schedule posts, and track growth. 

6. ROI: Grow your audience on LinkedIn without spending a lot of time 

7. Tutorial/ demo: [Link](https://youtu.be/oXLCqD_I9hQ?si=uNmRqg0mOExV46XK) 


2. **TheySaid 2.0** 

  1. Description: 10x your insights with AI surveys and interviews.  

2. Category: Surveys 

3. Do they provide a free trial: Yes 

4. Core features: AI survey creator, AI conversation upgrades, AI insights analysis, AI action items. 

5. ROI: Time saved in audience survey 

6. Website: [https://www.theysaid.io/](https://www.theysaid.io/) 

7. Tutorial/ demo: [Link](https://youtu.be/BurxF1990Ok?si=Q_k6eUbsTIeVhJ6_) 


3. **Digits AI Accounting** 

  1. Description: It is the first end-to-end accounting platform of the AI era.  

2. Category: Accounting 

3. Do they provide a free trial: No 

4. Website: [https://digits.com/](https://digits.com/) 

5. Core features: 24/7 AI-driven accounting, real-time insights, seamless bill pay and invoicing

6. ROI: Time saved in manual accounting work 

7. Tutorial/ demo: [Link](https://youtu.be/o43415BDF1o)  


4. **Duck AI** 

  1. Description: It is a free, private AI chat 

2. Category: AI chat 

3. Do they provide a free trial: Yes 

4. Website: [Link](https://duckduckgo.com/?q=DuckDuckGo+AI+Chat&ia=chat&duckai=1) 

5. Core features: Uses models like GPT-4o mini, Llama 3.3, and Claude 3 Haiku, chats are anonymized and not used for training.

6. ROI: Time saved in manual content research 

7. Tutorial/ demo: Not available 


5. **BannsAi**

  1. Description: Build your dream website in minutes with AI. 

2. Category: Graphic design 

3. Do they provide a free trial: Yes 

4. Website: [https://banns.ai/](https://banns.ai/) 

5. Core features: Cheap, copyright-free, and on-brand with logo and reference upload.  

6. ROI: Time saved in creating a banner 

7. Tutorial/ demo: [Link](https://youtu.be/VUkzzAqkiRQ) 


6. **AI Traffic Analysis** 

  1. Description: Track AI agent traffic from ChatGPT, Perplexity, and Gemini

2. Category: Digital marketing 

3. Do they provide a free trial: Yes 

4. Website: [Link](https://writesonic.com/generative-engine-optimization-geo/ai-traffic-analytics)  

5. Core features: Track all AI visits, identify top-performing content, and monitor growth trends 

6. Tutorial/ demo: [Link](https://youtu.be/LRE7_9CebGo?si=-wbC0xh-L8zKSEpS)  

7. ROI: Time saved for SEO experts


7. **IKI AI 2.0** 

  1. Description: It is an LLM-native space for your knowledge. 

2. Category: AI knowledge management

3. Do they provide a free trial: Yes 

4. Website: [https://iki.ai/](https://iki.ai/) 

5. Core features: Save URLs, YouTube videos, PDFs, txts, or sync your cloud drive, powered by SOTA LLMs, augmented with web search

6. Tutorial/ demo: [Link](https://youtu.be/Zd4BYtb1Py0) 

7. ROI: Time saved in internal workspace knowledge management. 


8. **Qodo Gen** 

  1. Description: Agentic coding to generate confidence, not just code.  

2. Category: Development 

3. Do they provide a free trial: Yes 

4. Website: [Link](https://plugins.jetbrains.com/plugin/21206-qodo-gen-formerly-codiumate-) 

5. Core features: Improve code quality, uncover potential bugs, understand your code better, ease your PR process, generate test suites and documentation.

6. Tutorial/ demo: Not available 

7. ROI: Time saved in development 


9. **Embra** 

  1. Description: Unify work with AI agents, meetings, CRM, research & email. 

2. Core features: Get meeting notes, track work, use AI agents, and more. 

3. Category: Workspace productivity management 

4. Do they provide a free trial: Yes 

5. Website: [https://www.embra.ai/](https://www.embra.ai/)

6. Tutorial/ demo: [Link](https://youtu.be/zuLuEa_ezz8) 

7. ROI: Time saved in manual operations work 


10. **Wispr Flow for Windows** 

  1. Description: It lets you speak naturally and see your words perfectly formatted, no extra edits, no typos.  

2. Category: Content creation 

3. Do they provide a free trial: Yes 

4. Website: [https://wisprflow.ai/](https://wisprflow.ai/) 

5. Tutorial/ demo: [Link](https://youtu.be/9KqGpxtsawc)

column7: üéØ¬†Why I‚Äôm Only Focusing On One Thing Before 2026
column9:
Hey friends,

Hope you‚Äôre doing well üôå

For the past few weeks, I‚Äôve been completely laser-focused on
building out our new Lifestyle Business Academy - it‚Äôs basically
the next evolution of the $1k Challenge, helping people build
sustainable businesses that fit around the life they want to
live.

Even though my team and I have been working on it for a while
now, it‚Äôs not yet finished. We‚Äôre still building the curriculum,
working out the whole onboarding process, refining the modules,
stuff like that, and because it‚Äôs my main priority for this
quarter, it‚Äôs always on my mind.

I‚Äôll be on a run (which I‚Äôve been doing pretty much every day
recently thanks to Momentum (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/o8u2p8v079tqh6gzrxpbvhqzwkwrrcohqe49l/3ohphdu34qr22dhp/aHR0cHM6Ly9nby5zcGFya2xlLnNvL3Byb2Rub3Rlcy1mb2N1cy0wMzEx
) üòâ) and suddenly have this random insight about how to structure
a module, or I‚Äôll be in the shower and all I‚Äôm thinking about is
names for our WhatsApp group chats.

It‚Äôs not stress exactly. It‚Äôs more like this low-level mental hum
that‚Äôs always there in the background, and even though I used to
think this was just me being overly enthusiastic about work,
there‚Äôs actually science behind why unfinished tasks seem to
haunt us like this.

It‚Äôs called the Zeigarnik Effect, and once you understand it, a
lot of things about productivity start to make sense.

Back in the 1920s, a psychologist named Bluma Zeigarnik was
sitting in a busy restaurant in Vienna and she noticed something
odd about the waiters. They could remember complex orders
perfectly while customers were still eating, but the moment the
bill was paid and the table cleared, they couldn‚Äôt remember a
single thing about that order.

She thought this was pretty fascinating so she decided to run an
experiment. She gave people a series of simple tasks to complete,
but she interrupted them halfway through some of the tasks, while
letting them finish others.

Later, when she tested their memory, people were twice as likely
to remember the interrupted tasks compared to the ones they‚Äôd
completed, which is super interesting.

And this is exactly what‚Äôs happening with the Lifestyle Business
Academy for me right now. My brain is holding onto it because
it‚Äôs unfinished business and trying to keep the task active in my
working memory so I‚Äôll come back and complete it.

While in some ways this is useful - those shower insights might
genuinely help improve the course üòÖ - it also means there‚Äôs this
constant background process running in my head that I can‚Äôt
switch off.

And this doesn‚Äôt just happen with big projects, your brain
literally holds on to all unfinished business - that side project
you started but abandoned, the book you‚Äôre reading but haven‚Äôt
touched in weeks, or that business idea that never left your
Apple Notes - which creates a lot of mental clutter.

So the solution isn‚Äôt to power through and somehow finish
everything.

The solution is to be way more selective about what you start in
the first place, and then actually finish the things you do start
before moving onto something new.

It sounds ridiculously simple, but it can be extremely hard to do
when we‚Äôre surrounded by messages telling us to ‚Äústart before
you‚Äôre ready‚Äù and ‚Äújust take action‚Äù and ‚Äúyou can do multiple
things at once.‚Äù

Most people don‚Äôt talk about the mental cost of starting too many
things without finishing them, so it might be useful to take a
look at your own goals or projects list and ask yourself: ‚ÄúWhat
would happen if I just picked one thing and finished it properly
before starting anything else?‚Äù

This is one of the core frameworks I teach in LifeOS (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/o8u2p8v079tqh6gzrxpbvhqzwkwrrcohqe49l/n2hohquv6ngxxnc0/aHR0cHM6Ly9hbGlhYmRhYWwuY29tL2xpZmVvcz91dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249Zm9jdXNfMDMmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPXByb2R1Y3RpdmVub3Rlcw==
) - choosing one main quest for work and one for life each
quarter (or every 90 days).

A main quest is a specific, measurable goal that would genuinely
move the needle if everything else stayed exactly the same, and
by forcing yourself to pick just one thing, you avoid spreading
your mental energy across ten half-started projects and you
actually give your brain permission to let go of all that other
stuff until your current quest is complete.

It‚Äôs been completely game-changing for how I approach my own
work, and it‚Äôs exactly why I can focus so clearly on the
Lifestyle Business Academy right now without feeling guilty about
all my other ‚Äúpotential projects‚Äù sat patiently waiting in
Notion.

If you want to learn more about main quests (plus a bunch of
other systems for designing your ideal life), you can check out
LifeOS here (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/o8u2p8v079tqh6gzrxpbvhqzwkwrrcohqe49l/n2hohquv6ngxxnc0/aHR0cHM6Ly9hbGlhYmRhYWwuY29tL2xpZmVvcz91dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249Zm9jdXNfMDMmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPXByb2R1Y3RpdmVub3Rlcw==
).

And if you do end up doing an audit of your unfinished projects,
hit reply and let me know which one thing you‚Äôd most want to
complete before the end of 2025 - I‚Äôd love to hear from you.

Have a great rest of your week üòä

Ali xx
